After I saw the exeption I changed my code to:
```
_publicRsa = RSA.Create();
_publicRsa.EdoFromXmlString(_options.PublicKey);
_issuerSigningKey = new RsaSecurityKey(_publicRsa);
            
_privateRsa = RSA.Create();
_privateRsa.EdoFromXmlString(_options.PrivateKey);
RsaSecurityKey privateKey = new RsaSecurityKey(_privateRsa);
_signingCredentials = new SigningCredentials(privateKey, SecurityAlgorithms.RsaSha256);
            
_jwtHeader = new JwtHeader(_signingCredentials);

//payload generation

string result = _jwtSecurityTokenHandler.WriteToken(new JwtSecurityToken(_jwtHeader, payload));
_publicRsa.Dispose();
_privateRsa.Dispose();
```
As you can see I removed the using statements and I dispose the RSAs myself and it now works. (Had to do this on both sides, when creating the token and when validating it).
I am not sure if this is an issue or feature but to me it seems that my old should still be working. 
This only appears when I run the app from the CLI, if I am debugging the application no such problems occur and the token is generated without problems. Really strange...

This is my first time ever writing something like this and I hope that I am now wasting your time and also that someone might find this useful.

Regards!

